                                        Basic Commands

	1-> pwd(path of current working directory) - It find out the path of current working 							     directory.
						     usage:
							   pwd 
	
	2-> cd (change Directory)- to navigate through the linux files and directory.it require 				   full path or the name of the directory,depending on the current 					   working directory we are in.
				   usage:
					cd directory name || path of directory
				   There are some shortcuts to help you navigate quickly:

					a-> cd .. to move one directory up.
					b-> cd to go straight to the home folder
					c-> cd- to move to your previous directory
	
	3-> ls(list command) - used to view the contents of a directory.
				usage:
					ls directory name || directory path
			       There are variations you can use with the ls command:
				a-> ls -R will list all the files in the sub-directories as well.
				b-> ls -a will show the hidden files.
				c-> ls -al will list the files and directories with detailed 					    information like the permissions, size etc.


	4-> cat (concatenate command) - used to list the contents of a file on the standard output.
					usage cat filename.extension
					other ways to use the cat command:
						a-> cat > filename creates a new file
						b-> cat filename1 filename2>filename3 joins two 						    files (1 and 2) and stores the output of them 							    in a new file (3)
						c->to convert a file to upper or lower case use, 							   cat filename | tr a-z A-Z >output.txt
						usage:
							 cat>con.txt
							 cat con.txt
							 cat con.txt con2.txt>output.txt
							 

	5-> cp (copy command) - Use the cp command to copy files from the current directory to a 					different directory.
				usage:
					 cp copy.txt ../Downloads/ 

	6-> mv (move command) - a)use of the mv command is to move files, although it can also be 					  used to rename files.
				b)To rename files, the Linux command is mv oldname.ext newname.ext


				usage:
					mv test.txt ../Documents/
					

	7-> mkdir (make directory command) - use to make a new directory.
						usage:
							mkdir vikram

						There are extra mkdir commands as well:
						a-> To generate a new directory inside another 							    directory, use this Linux basic command-
							mkdir vikram/testing

	8-> rmdir (remove directory) - to delete a directory, use the rmdir command. However, 					       rmdir only allows you to delete empty directories.
					usage:
						rmdir testing/

	9-> rm (remove command) - used to delete directories and the contents within them.
					usage:
						rm -r /remove/testing/ 							rm test.txt

	10-> touch - allows to create a blank new file through the Linux command line.
			usage:
				touch index.html

	11-> find - search for files and directories with in a given directory.
			usage:
				find ./touch -name test.txt

	12-> grep - use to search through all the text in a given file
			usage:
				grep world grep.txt

	13-> sudo(SuperUser Do) - enables to perform tasks that require administrative or root 					  permissions.
					usage:
						sudo dpkg -i code_1.54.1-1614898113_amd64.deb

	14-> df  - to get a report on the systemâ€™s disk space usage, shown in percentage and KBs.
			usage:
				df 
				df -m

	15-> du(Disk Usage) - to check how much space a file or a directory takes.
				usage:
					du filename||path of file (depending on the current 									   directory)
					du -h filename||path of file (depending on the current 									      directory)
	16-> head - used to view the first lines of any text file. By default, it will show the 		    first ten lines, but you can change this number to your liking.

			usage:
				head -n 2 ./basic\ commands/head/head.txt 

	17-> tail - This one has a similar function to the head command, but instead of showing 		    the first lines, the tail command will display the last ten lines of a text 		    file.
				usage:
					tail -n 2 ./basic\ commands/head/head.txt

	18-> diff(Difference) - compares the contents of two files line by line. After analyzing 					the files, it will output the lines that do not match.

					usage:
						diff test.txt test1.txt

	19-> tar - used to archive multiple files into a tarball.
		   also use to do many function with archive file.
			usage:

			 tar -cf archive.tar diff grep //create archive.tar file having deff and 								 grep folder
			 tar -tvf archive.tar // list all the file in archive file verbosely
			 tar xf archive.tar //extract all the files in archive file
			 tar -rf archive.tar head // append file to the end of an archive

	20-> chmod - used to change the read, write, and execute permissions of files and 			     directories.
				usage:
					chmod u=rwx,g=rx,o=r head.txt
			 
	21-> chmod - chown command enables you to change or transfer the ownership of a file to 		     the specified username.
			usage:
				chown vikram ./Desktop/basic\ command/head/head.txt

	22-> jobs -  display all current jobs along with their statuses.jobs are processes started 			     by shell.

				usage:
					jobs

	23-> kill - terminate a unresponsive program manually by using kill command.it send the 		    certain signal to app and instruct the app to terminate itself.

			usually used two signals are:
				a-> SIGTERM - requests a program to stop running and gives it some 							time to save all of its progress.
				b-> SIGKILL - forces programs to stop immediately. Unsaved 						      progress will be lost.

				usage:
					kill [signal option] PID //PID of a process can be found 						by using ps(process name) ux

	24-> ping - check connectivity status to a server.
			usage:
				ping google.com

	25-> wget - download files from the internet with the help of the wget command.

			usage:
				wget https://unsplash.com/photos/hTB6iloRoLg/download?force=true
				wget -b https://unsplash.com/photos/hTB6iloRoLg/download?force=true
				// download in background

	26-> uname - print detailed information about your Linux system like the machine name, 			     operating system, kernel, and so on.

			usage:
				uname				
				uname -p
				uname -r etc...

	27-> history ->  review the commands entered before.
				usage:
					history

	28-> man(manual) -> show the manual instruction of the command.

				usage:
					man grep

	29-> echo -> used to move some data into a file.
			usage:
				echo my name is vikram>>test.txt

	30-> zip -> to compress your files into a zip archive, and use the unzip command to 			    extract the zipped files from a zip archive.
			usage:
				zip concat.zip ./concat
				unzip concat.zip

	31-> useradd -> useradd is used to create a new user.
			USAGE:
				useradd vikram

	32-> userdel -> userdel is use to delete the user.
				usage:
					userdel vikram

					

				 
			 




	




					
